Sunhvindar came to Russia to earn money in 2005. He stayed in the capital, selling Indian knitwear. He was doing quite well. He had enough money for rent, food, and help for his family.

Quiet Indians in general are good for communication. Our compatriot decided to talk to Singh, but the men failed to understand each other, the conversation turned into a fight, and luck was on the Indian's side.

Luck, but not Themis. For causing bodily harm, he was sentenced to three years in prison. He served from call to call in a penal colony for foreign nationals in Mordovia. At present there is no such colony, the newcomers serve their sentences together with the Russians.

After his release Sunhvindar returned to Moscow. He met a girl and fell in love. Tatiana, a native Muscovite, reciprocated. The couple soon started living together.

The Indian looked for a long time for a job, but Moscow does not believe in tears and former foreign prisoners without secondary education. Singh decided to return to his old business. Business required leaving for India. There were no obstacles to departure. Difficulties came later. Russia would not let a convicted person into the country. Then Sunhvindar resorted to cunning. He simply bought fake documents in someone else's name.

Perhaps, such a practice is common in India. How else to explain the fact that lovers wished to marry legally and out of the blue submitted false documents to the registry office? As usual, they were "checked out" there, and the bridegroom was sentenced to 14 months. He was sent to our region to serve his second sentence.

After his release, Sunhvindar has no intention of returning to India. He connects his future with Russia. I am sure that his relatives will understand and not condemn him.

WARNING: LONG BORING POST YOU PROBABLY DON'T CARE ABOUT SO FEEL FREE TO SCROLL PAST IT

Remember those weird Medieval Maltese names I talked about and how their meaning/origins are not as clear as a name from the same period of time like, say, "Paulu"?
Well, as I decided to finally include them in my CKII Maltese mod, I decided to look around the main culture file for any potential names to look too similar for it to be a coincidence that they are not linked.
I am doing this for regal numbering purposes. Basically what it does is if for example the count of Malta is a character of the Italian culture and is named "Giovanni", and he is formerly "Giovanni II, Count of Malta",
and his heir is somehow a French guy with the name "Jean", when the French guy inherits, he becomes "Jean III, Count of Malta" not "Jean I, Count of Malta". Basically, keeping consistency between a same name
but in different languages. At first I did not want to add the weird names because at a first glance, I could not find the equivalent to link them to and I'd hate to have the name be actually present in the game and I do
not link it to it out of ignorance. For "Azimundinu", I am pretty sure I can link it up to "Azim". I didn't do it before because I am not 100% sure they're linked. But today, I just found another possible origin to another name.
"Ansaldinu" might be a local derivative of the name "Ensaldus", A name which in-game is labelled as Suebi. I googled it and found this Wiki link (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Germanic_personal_names_in_Galicia#Masculine_roots) , with the name listed there. I think the names are too similar for it to be a coincidence, and having people in Malta at that time with origins from Iberia is a fact.

>India
I feel like most expats are coming from first world nations where they're being paid USD, Euro or in my unfortunate case CAD.
Anyone who expects to live in a high end expat neighborhood is probably making north of $2500 USD take-home a month and can easily afford the rent (especially with how cheap everything else is) and anyone making less than that is probably fine with living in a smaller city or a less affluent neighborhood and paying half their rent back home for a place that's as nice or nicer.
To put things in to perspective for you, I'll keep currency in USD for simplicities sake, a mediocre 1bdr apartment in a small city where I live is about $750 USD if you're lucky, but more likely closer to $900-950. This is to enjoy the privilege of living alone. In a big flashy city like Toronto you're looking at anywhere between $1500 and $2200 for a 1 bedroom but could probably get into $3000-3500 for one of the better neighborhoods. All of these prices are converted to cold hard USD and not CAD (it's actually more expensive for us relatively speaking - we don't really earn 25% more across the board)
Meanwhile in Thailand I can get a pretty fucking nice apartment for $750 USD - I imagine that'd get me a nice place in one of the better Bangkok neighborhoods. It might not get me a super high end luxury suite in the most affluent part of the city but I'd still be living like a king vs cramped into a shoebox apartment.

>implying that they already don't
Captchas (Completely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart) are a type of challenge-response test used to determine whether a user is a human or a computer. They are often used as a security measure to prevent automated programs from accessing certain websites or services.

Using human slaves to solve captchas would be unethical and illegal. It is important to respect the rights and dignity of all individuals, and to refrain from engaging in activities that exploit or harm others.

It is also important to recognize that captchas are not foolproof and can sometimes be defeated by sophisticated attackers. Therefore, it is important for website owners and developers to consider using a variety of security measures to protect their sites and services, rather than relying on a single solution like captchas.

En stormakt är en stor och inflytelserik nation med betydande ekonomiska, militära och politiska resurser. En supermakt är en stormakt som har en dominerande roll på den globala scenen och har den största militära, ekonomiska och politiska makten i världen. Supermakter har också ofta en stark kultur och ideologi som spridits över världen och som har en stor inverkan på andra länder.

Det finns en del överlapp mellan begreppen stormakt och supermakt, men det finns också viktiga skillnader. En stormakt kan ha betydande makt och inflytande, men det behöver inte vara en supermakt. En supermakt, å andra sidan, har den starkaste militära, ekonomiska och politiska makten i världen och har en dominerande roll på den globala scenen. En supermakt kan också ha en stark kultur och ideologi som spridits över världen och som har en stor inverkan på andra länder.

They just happen to translate to the same English word. This is where the confusion lies.
"Bcё eщё" means "still" as in "until now".
"Bce-тaки" means "still" as in "nonetheless".
It's the difference between "I still want to go" and "Still, I want to go".

Doubt there are books written in interslavic. Old church slavonic has at least the bible. Afaik interslavic isn't really meant as a language to converse in, but rather one that you can speak or write in order for most slavs to understand you. So you can learn one language abd get by in a dozen countries. Or at a pan-slavic meetup, speakers could translate their speeches to interslavic (without actually speaking the language) so that everyone can understand without an interpreter. Traditionally that role would have been filled by Russian, since all slavs used to be under the Soviet sphere of influence, but now Russia is a bit of a touchy subject, and giving their language such a privilliged position would anger some people, especially poles and czechs (and guess what, interslavic was made by a Czech guy)

>Ich spinne NICHT.
Spinnen is mainly used in a playful way and has a childish feel. If you are talking about actual mental illness (in this case I assume schizophrenia), you would say "Ich bin nicht verrückt!"
>Ich weiß, dass er diejenigen Zahlen austauschte.
diejenigen is way too fancy. Either "diese", or if you want to say "those" to contrast with some other, closer numbers, you would use "jene". Here, only one set of numbers is mentioned, so "jene" is wrong.
Präteritum if rare in day-to-day speech and it sounds especially weird here. Use Perfekt "ausgetauscht hat".
>Hast du etwas in deiner Tasche?
Good.
>Genau wie ich gedacht habe. Du hast den Akku entfernt.
Genau wie ich dachte.
Side note: Officially, "Akku" means only rechargeable batteries, while "Batterie" means non-rechargable ones. In reality Akku is used for both.
>Kannst du in deiner Brusttasche reichen und sag mir, was drinnen ist?
in deine Brusttache

und mir sagen, was da drin(nen) ist.
Or: was in ihr drin ist. Keep in mind, "drin" is colloquial.

Er hat den Idioten im Copyshop dazu gebracht, für ihn zu lügen.

Hast du (immer) noch nicht gemerkt, dass das hier echt ist?
Dieser was?
wahr = true. echt = real.

Willst du mir sagen, dass ein Mann/eine Person einfach so fällt / einfach so fallen kann.
Maybe you could add the idiomatic "aus heiterem Himmel", which captures the same "with no reason" as "just happens to".

I figured out what the problem with "austauschte" and "ausgetauscht hat" was. Take a look at these two sentences:
>Ich weis, dass sie die Zahlten ausgetauscht hat. (I know that she swapped the numbers)
>Es geschah, wählend sie die Zahlen austauschte. (It happened while she was swapping the numbers)
Perfekt is a completed action, while Präteritum is an ongoing one (at the point in time the sentence is describing). This distinction is a lot weaker than slavic perfective/impefective verbs or english simple past/past progressive. The thing with Präteritum being rare in speech applies to the second case, where you could also use Perfekt
>Es geschah, während sie die Zahlen aushetauscht hat.

Präteritum is common with haben, sein and the modal verbs (möchten, können, werden...)
denken can go either way. As a rule of thumb, the more common a word is, the more often it is used in Präteritum in casual speech. It's the same rason why in English commonly used verbs have irregular past forms. If something is used often, it resits simplification.
I should have written multiple variants for "Just as I thought"
>Das habe ich mir doch gedacht
>Genau wie ich es mir dachte
>Genau wie ich's mir gedacht habe
>Dacht' ich's mir doch
